Here's the complete implementation using the Hexi library:

```cpp
#include <hexi/hexi.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <span>
#include <string_view>

struct MessagePacket {
    uint32_t header;
    std::string_view message;
};

MessagePacket read_header_and_message(const std::span<const uint8_t> buffer) {
    // Create a buffer adaptor from the input buffer
    hexi::buffer_adaptor adaptor(buffer);

    // Read the header (uint32_t) using buffer_adaptor's read method
    uint32_t header = adaptor.read<uint32_t>();

    // Get the remaining data after the header
    auto remaining_data = adaptor.remaining();

    // Create a binary_stream from the remaining data
    hexi::binary_stream stream(remaining_data);

    // Use binary_stream's view method to get a view of the null-terminated string
    // The view method for null-terminated strings returns a string_view up to the null terminator
    std::string_view message = stream.view<std::string_view>();

    return MessagePacket{header, message};
}
```

This implementation:

1. Creates a `buffer_adaptor` from the input buffer span
2. Uses `buffer_adaptor::read<uint32_t>()` to read the header value
3. Gets the remaining data after the header using `adaptor.remaining()`
4. Creates a `binary_stream` from the remaining data
5. Uses `binary_stream::view<std::string_view>()` to get a view of the null-terminated string (this method automatically handles finding the null terminator)
6. Returns a `MessagePacket` containing both the header and the message view

The `binary_stream::view<std::string_view>()` method is specifically designed to handle null-terminated strings - it will return a `std::string_view` that contains all characters up to (but not including) the null terminator.

