Looking at the Hexi library's `dynamic_buffer` interface, I need to implement a function that peeks at data without advancing the read pointer. The key is to use the buffer's data access methods that don't modify the read position.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/dynamic_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <algorithm>

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
std::vector<uint8_t> peek_data_from_buffer(const hexi::dynamic_buffer<block_size>& buffer, size_t bytes_to_peek) {
    // Determine how much data is actually available to peek
    size_t available_bytes = buffer.size();
    bytes_to_peek = std::min(bytes_to_peek, available_bytes);

    // Create result vector with the appropriate size
    std::vector<uint8_t> result;
    result.reserve(bytes_to_peek);

    // Use the buffer's data() method to access the underlying data without advancing read pointer
    // The data() method typically returns a pointer to the current read position
    const uint8_t* data_ptr = buffer.data();

    // Copy the requested number of bytes into the result vector
    if (data_ptr != nullptr && bytes_to_peek > 0) {
        result.insert(result.end(), data_ptr, data_ptr + bytes_to_peek);
    }

    return result;
}
```

Alternative implementation using the buffer's iteration capabilities:

```cpp
#include <hexi/dynamic_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <algorithm>

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
std::vector<uint8_t> peek_data_from_buffer(const hexi::dynamic_buffer<block_size>& buffer, size_t bytes_to_peek) {
    // Determine how much data is actually available to peek
    size_t available_bytes = buffer.size();
    bytes_to_peek = std::min(bytes_to_peek, available_bytes);

    if (bytes_to_peek == 0) {
        return std::vector<uint8_t>();
    }

    // Create result vector
    std::vector<uint8_t> result;
    result.reserve(bytes_to_peek);

    // Use the buffer's iterator or data access methods to copy without modifying read position
    // This approach uses the buffer's const iterator capabilities
    auto it = buffer.begin();
    for (size_t i = 0; i < bytes_to_peek && it != buffer.end(); ++i, ++it) {
        result.push_back(*it);
    }

    return result;
}
```

The first implementation is more efficient as it uses bulk copy operations. Both implementations correctly peek at the data without advancing the read pointer by using const-qualified access methods that don't modify the buffer's internal state.

